ce:section.ce:para:
The N2 adsorption/desorption isotherms at −196 °C of the catalysts are shown in Fig. 2
                        a (data included in Table 1
                        ). All materials exhibited a type IV isotherm, according to the IUPAC classification [22], with narrow H4 type hysteresis. This means that the materials are micro-mesoporous carbons, as shown in Fig. 2b. Therefore the treatment with sulfuric acid does not affect significantly their total pore volume, however, a decrease in specific surface area was observed for the ACS1 sample, as previously reported [8,13,14,23,24]. It can be observed that ACS1 has larger meso-macropore volume than other catalysts. The PSD curves presented in Fig. 2b indicated that the modified activated carbons were very similar in terms of pore size distributions.
